<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-roots" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Roots and Solving for the Base</title>

  <p> We saw in <xref ref="fact-rootasapower"/> that we can view a square root, or cube root, or any root as just a particular type of exponent, and in fact, that's often how we enter them into a calculator when we can't compute them in our heads.</p>

  <p>
    Sometimes we have information about the root of a value, but we want the value itself.
    Other times, we'll have information about the value after it has been raised to a power, but want information about the original value.
    Because terms like <q>square</q> and <q>cube</q> get thrown into the mix when we're talking about both the second or third power <alert>OR</alert> the second or third root... the language can get confusing.
  </p>

  <p>
    We've learned and practiced how to solve linear equations in <xref ref="sec-lines"></xref>, now we want to be able to solve equations like <m>\sqrt[3]{x}=8</m> or <m>r^2=42</m>.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="example-cuberoot">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>\sqrt[3]{x}=8</m> for <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        You might read this equation as, <q>What number cube rooted equals 8?</q>
        This can also be thought of as, <q>8 cubed is what number?</q>
        To solve this, we can cube both sides of the equation because cube roots and cubing are inverse functions, they <q>undo</q> each other.   
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[3]{x} \amp = 8</mrow>
          <mrow>\left(\sqrt[3]{x}\right)^3 \amp = \left(8\right)^3</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = 8 \times 8 \times 8</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = 512</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="example-r-squared">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>r^2=42</m> for <m>r</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The equation reads, <q>What number squared is 42?</q>
        This can also be thought of as, <q>The square root of 42 is what number?</q>
        To solve this, we can take the square root of both sides of the equation, again because square roots and squaring are inverse operations.  
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>r^2\amp = 42</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{r^2} \amp = \sqrt{42} \approx 6.4807</mrow>
        </md>
        Note that <m>6.4807 \times 6.4807</m> is 42, but <m>-6.4807 \times -6.4807 = 42</m> as well.  So <m>r</m> is really <m>\pm 6.4807</m>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <insight>
    <p>
    We can (and should!) always check our answer(s) when solving equations; simply go back to the start and plug in the value(s) and see if it works out.
    </p>
  </insight>

  <fact xml:id="fact-even-roots">
  <title>Even Powers and Roots</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Raising a negative number to an even power results in a positive value; <m>(-2)^4 = (-2)(-2)(-2)(-2) = (4)(4) = 16</m>.
        So, an equation like <m>x^n = -1234</m> where <m>n</m> is even will have no solution. 
        This also means, that if we input a negative value into an even root, <m>\sqrt[n]{-1234}</m> like we would to solve the above equation, most calculators will produce and error.
        As we see in <xref ref="example-r-squared"/>, when determining the solution to an equation with an even power, we will need to consider negative values as well.
        A calculator will always produce just the positive answer when you input <m>\sqrt[n]{\#}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </fact>

  <fact xml:id="fact-odd-roots">
    <title>Odd Powers and Roots</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Raising a negative number to an odd power results in a negative value; <m>(-2)^5 = (-2)(-2)(-2)(-2)(-2) = (4)(4)(-2) = -32</m>.
          So, an equation like <m>x^m = -1234</m> where <m>m</m> is odd will have a <alert>unique</alert> solution; what we get when we input <m>\sqrt[m]{-1234}</m> into a calculator.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A number cubed is -27, what number (or numbers) is it?
      </p>
      <p>
        A number squared is -64, what number (or numbers) is it?
      </p>
      <p>
        A number raised to the fourth power is 81, what number (or numbers) is it? 
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <q>A number cubed is -27,</q> translates to <m>x^3 = -27</m>.
        We can solve this by taking the cube root of both sides:
        <md>
          <mrow>x^3 \amp -27</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt[3]{x^3} \amp = \sqrt[3]{-27}</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = -3</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>A number squared is -64,</q> translates to <m>x^2 = -64</m>.
        This will have no solution, since any number raised to an even power is positive, <xref ref="fact-even-roots"/>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>A number raised to the fourth power is 81,</q> translates to <m>x^4 = 81</m>.
        We can solve this in one step by taking the fourth root of both sides, which is easy with a calculator.
        Most of these types of equations require a calculator to solve, but this one has fairly friendly numbers.
      </p>
      <p>
        We might recognize 81 as a <q>perfect square</q>, that is <m>81 = 9^2</m>. So,
          <md>
            <mrow>x^4 \amp = 81</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt{x^4} \amp = \sqrt{81}</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2 \amp = 9</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt{x^2} \amp = \sqrt{9}</mrow>
            <mrow>x \amp = 3</mrow>
          </md>
        Since this involves an even power, we consider if a negative might also be a solution:
        <me>
          (-3)^4 = (-3)(-3)(-3)(-3) = (9)(9) = 81.
        </me>
        So a number raised to the fourth power that equals 81 could be <m>\pm 3</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>  

  <p>
    In some cases, we'll need even more steps to solve an equation involving roots or powers. 
    Before we attempt to undo a root with a power or vice versa, we need to make sure the we've isolated that term.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>2\sqrt{x} + 1 = 13</m> for <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We first aim to isolate the <m>\sqrt{x}</m> term on one side:
        <md>
          <mrow>2\sqrt{x} + 1 \amp = 13</mrow>
          <mrow>2\sqrt{x} + 1 - 1\amp = 13 - 1</mrow>
          <mrow>2\sqrt{x} \amp = 12</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{2sqrt{x}}{2} \amp = \frac{12}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{x} \amp = 6</mrow>
        </md>
        To undo the square root, we square both sides:
        <md>
          <mrow>\left(\sqrt{x}\right)^2 \amp = 6^2</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp 36</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      It is good practice to consider potential negative solutions, but in this case, a negative value for <m>x</m> will not work since we cannot take the even root of a negative number.
    </solution>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>\sqrt{2x} + 1 = 13</m> and <m>2\sqrt{x+1} = 13</m> for <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt{2x} + 1 \amp = 13</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{2x} + 1 - 1 \amp = 13 - 1</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{2x} \amp = 12</mrow>
          <mrow>\left(\sqrt{2x}\right)^2 \amp = 12^2</mrow>
          <mrow>2x \amp = 144</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{2x}{2} \amp = \frac{144}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = 72</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>2\sqrt{x+1} \amp = 13</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{2\sqrt{x+1}}{2} \amp = \frac{13}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{x+1} \amp = 6.5</mrow>
          <mrow>\left(\sqrt{x+1}\right)^2 \amp = (6.5)^2</mrow>
          <mrow>x+1 \amp = 42.5</mrow>
          <mrow>x + 1 - 1 \amp = 42.5 - 1</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = 41.5</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      In both cases, these are the only solution.
    </solution>
  </exercise>


  

</section>